Linux Perf Performance Analysis Tool

Jan 5, 2025

Linux Perf

Perf is powerful: it can instrument CPU performance counters, tracepoints, kprobes, and uprobes (dynamic tracing). It is capable of lightweight profiling. It is also included in the Linux kernel, under tools/perf, and is frequently updated and enhanced.

Performance counters are CPU hardware registers that count hardware events such as instructions executed, cache-misses suffered, or branches mispredicted. They form a basis for profiling applications to trace dynamic control flow and identify hotspots. perf provides rich generalized abstractions over hardware specific capabilities. Among others, it provides per task, per CPU and per-workload counters, sampling on top of these and source code event annotation.

Tracepoints are instrumentation points placed at logical locations in code, such as for system calls, TCP/IP events, file system operations, etc. These have negligible overhead when not in use, and can be enabled by the perf command to collect information including timestamps and stack traces. perf can also dynamically create tracepoints using the kprobes and uprobes frameworks, for kernel and userspace dynamic tracing. The possibilities with these are endless.

Profiling : In software engineering, profiling is a form of dynamic program analysis that measures, for example, the space or time complexity of a program, the usage of particular instructions, or the frequency and duration of function calls.

Perf : perf is a performance analyzing tool in Linux, available from Linux kernel version 2.6.31 in 2009. Userspace controlling utility, named perf, is accessed from the command line and provides a number of subcommands; it is capable of statistical profiling of the entire system.

Kernel : The kernel is a computer program at the core of a computerâ€™s operating system and generally has complete control over everything in the system. It is the portion of the operating system code that is always resident in memory, and facilitates interactions between hardware and software components.

install and configure

sudo apt install linux-tools-$(uname -r) linux-tools-generic
sudo apt install linux-tools-common
sudo apt install linux-tools-generic
sudo apt install linux-tools-`uname -r`


#!/bin/bash
sudo mount -o remount,mode=755 /sys/kernel/debug
sudo mount -o remount,mode=755 /sys/kernel/debug/tracing
echo "0" | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/kptr_restrict
echo "-1" | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/perf_event_paranoid
sudo chown `whoami` /sys/kernel/debug/tracing/uprobe_events
sudo chmod a+rw /sys/kernel/debug/tracing/uprobe_events


sudo su -
echo 0 > /proc/sys/kernel/perf_event_paranoid
exit
mkdir -p perf
sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf
# add this line
kernel.perf_event_paranoid = 0
sudo sysctl -p

echo 0: This part of the command writes the value 0 into the perf_event_paranoid parameter, which controls the access level. Setting it to 0 grants the lowest level of restriction, allowing all users (including non-root users) to access performance monitoring events.

Add dynamic probe, trigger it and report

We can add dynamic probe without kernel recompilation, 

sudo perf probe 'tcp_v4_connect'

system knows where to insert tcp_v4_connect probe, because tcp_v4_connect is standard function that we can find in kallsyms.

upgautam@amd:~/Desktop/perf$ sudo cat /proc/kallsyms | grep tcp_v4_connect
ffffffff92bfd420 T __pfx_tcp_v4_connect
ffffffff92bfd430 T tcp_v4_connect
ffffffff939a2b08 r __ksymtab_tcp_v4_connect

ffffffff92bfd430 is the memory address where tcp_v4_connect function is defined. So, system adds probe here.  The probe is then added dynamically using kprobe mechanism inside function body as we know the function memory address is ffffffff92bfd430.

upgautam@amd:~/Desktop/perf$ sudo perf probe -l
  probe:tcp_v4_connect (on tcp_v4_connect)

Not using any tools, I could do kprobe at the same symbol tcp_v4_connect programmatically as, 

//kprobe_tcp.c
#include <linux/module.h>
#include <linux/kernel.h>
#include <linux/kprobes.h>

/* Pre-handler: called before the probed instruction is executed */
static int handler_pre(struct kprobe *p, struct pt_regs *regs)
{
    printk(KERN_INFO "kprobe: tcp_v4_connect triggered.\n");
    return 0; // Continue execution
}

/* Post-handler: called after the probed instruction is executed */
static void handler_post(struct kprobe *p, struct pt_regs *regs, unsigned long flags)
{
    printk(KERN_INFO "kprobe: tcp_v4_connect completed.\n");
}

/* Fault-handler: called if there is a fault during probing */
static int handler_fault(struct kprobe *p, struct pt_regs *regs, int trapnr)
{
    printk(KERN_INFO "kprobe: fault at tcp_v4_connect.\n");
    return 0; // Let the kernel handle the fault
}

/* kprobe structure */
static struct kprobe kp = {
    .symbol_name = "tcp_v4_connect", // Name of the function to probe
    .pre_handler = handler_pre,     // Function called before the probed function
    .post_handler = handler_post,   // Function called after the probed function
    .fault_handler = handler_fault, // Function called on fault
};

/* Module initialization */
static int __init kprobe_init(void)
{
    int ret;

    printk(KERN_INFO "Registering kprobe at tcp_v4_connect...\n");
    ret = register_kprobe(&kp); // Register the kprobe
    if (ret < 0) {
        printk(KERN_ERR "Failed to register kprobe: %d\n", ret);
        return ret;
    }

    printk(KERN_INFO "kprobe registered at %s\n", kp.symbol_name);
    return 0;
}

/* Module cleanup */
static void __exit kprobe_exit(void)
{
    unregister_kprobe(&kp); // Unregister the kprobe
    printk(KERN_INFO "kprobe unregistered from tcp_v4_connect.\n");
}

module_init(kprobe_init);
module_exit(kprobe_exit);

MODULE_LICENSE("GPL");
MODULE_AUTHOR("Your Name");
MODULE_DESCRIPTION("Kprobe at tcp_v4_connect");

more examples

sudo perf stat -e cycles -p <pid> this shows the number of cpu cycles consumed by process. sudo perf diff perf.data.old perf.data.new to compare two perf data files. Use sudo perf record -e mem-loads,mem-stores -p <pid> and sudo perf report to track memory allocations. Use sudo perf record -e context-switches -p <pid> and sudo perf report to profile context switches. For io latency sudo perf record -e block:block_rq_issue,block:block_rq_complete . Use sudo perf record -e power:energy-pkg to record power consumption. use sudo perf trace -e syscalls:sys_enter_read to trace function tracing, and several other.
